The SSD in Prague doesn't know Voldemort or the bakery.
The new ČSSD councilors in the capital will, it seems, have to overcome the obvious language barriers in order for the members of the Prague City Council and the City Council to understand their renewed ODS colleagues.
Aktuálně.cz period "tested" the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the slang markup language that has emerged in the last few years in the Council, when the current coalition members ruled Prague.
The coded dictionary used by the political cream of Prague during the previous period, Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the metropolis' best-known characters, situations and causes.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councillors hardly understand these well-known concepts.
At least, that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I don't know, to be honest".
"I'm more of a novice in Prague politics", said the city councilor for culture Lukáš Kaucký during the examination of the terminology of "college".
And as for the veteran politician, Karel Březina reacted the same.
You may be familiar with the concept of a golf hole.
"It's probably the only expression of all the ones you've asked me that I use from time to time".
"If not, I usually don't use slang".
From the glossary, whose definitions were published by the newspaper Aktuálně.cz last June before the ODS voting congress, the editorial team chose six examples, particularly those that are especially related to the Prague municipal authorities.
The socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "Prague's largest golf hole", "go to the pastry shop", "bull's neck", "betrayal of the capital" and "armor".
Three councillors agreed to take the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will be responsible for education in Prague in the future, initially agreed, but did not return to the phone.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, flatly refused to do so.
"I don't get involved in these things and I don't value how civic democrats have fun".
"What I do care about is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programmes", he said.
As we have seen, supposedly councillor Lukáš Kaucký would not have realized that the previous title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký, the word "Voldemort" means nothing; the only term he got right on the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"It's about the Blanka tunnel", says Kaucký, who immediately adds: "But I know it from the news".
"I'm going to have to sign up for a language course", he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one to recognize the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also Environment Councillor Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both social democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; moreover, he suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think he means to go to a company in Prague"; it is soon revealed to Plachý that it is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge he obtained from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the participants in the survey, no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms exists among the Social Democrats.
"I asked my colleagues, but it really seems we have nothing in common".
"Instead, among us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations or we make word games with the names", says Prague's ČSSD president, Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call Hulda.
"In school they called me Bříza, but I don't know if my classmates also call me that", confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz tested the name and it works.
For his party colleagues, Weinert is either Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), the representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they associated before the election deceptions during the party's sponsorship, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") from some of his colleagues.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that the social democrats tolerate in the party's internal discourse.
Hulínský doesn't like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz discovered even other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The doctor of the rights of the batons" seems to recall that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in law at the police academy in Bratislava.
Government wants to limit torture of "witches", says brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work for health reasons, single and without children.
Women who "become" witches are sent to a secluded area, so they don't harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such sin".
"Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help with the work and have children", explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, is in charge of a special home for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an informative pamphlet that should help to prevent witch hunts.
This has a catch, though.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read", warns Die Standard newspaper about the drawbacks of written awareness-raising.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and set her on fire.
The news was on the BBC.
The authors claim it was due to an unfortunate combination of circumstances.
According to her account, the woman was caught in the oil used for ritual anointing.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "exorcise the evil spirits" of the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "Soul eaters have always been a danger".
While in Burkina Faso the Government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the President still participated in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a massive witch hunt allegedly linked to his death and attempted to kill the president himself through black magic".
"To help him, he brought in shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, forcibly took randomly selected men and women from the Gambian villages to the president's property in Kanilai", said Amnesty International in its report.
At the farm, the people arrested had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay at the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
Bakala tenant: heating himself with coal stoves and signing a higher rent
The elderly and frail man walked through the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under her arm she carried some documents with the new lease agreements for three floors: hers, her daughter's and her son's, who is serving a sentence.
All three of them just got their asses kicked by the rent liberalisation.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the child will pay 4,100 crowns from next year for a two-room flat with a separate kitchen in the second category.
"In addition, it has no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler", the man points with his finger at his son's new contract, over which he has full authority to sign.
"But I signed it", he explains, half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes a gesture.
"Everyone says one thing", he says with a grim face.
Ostrava is becoming a great laboratory for liberalization.
After New Year's it will happen with the vast majority of flats that, in the Czech Republic, were until now under a regulated rent.
So Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and by 9 a.m. on Tuesday it was already full.
Right by the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to take numbers.
"Rental 2011", can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When pressed, a number is printed on a piece of paper.
It hardly takes him long to read "157" and the number appears on the big screen at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrive to inquire, but the crowd in the hall is not here for the new tenants.
Most people come to solve the usual problems, as in the old days: requests for repairs, insurance issues and similar matters.
Letters with the new lease agreements will reach the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments belonging to RPG in Ostrava around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters an increase in the rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18th, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been running for a week, so it's just starting", the workers who are in the shop respond after a brief hesitation when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Liberalisation and the old miners' flats in Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already dealt with loud and clear by the vice-president of the Parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek of the ČSSD, from Ostrava, and now they appear continuously in the area's newspapers.
"Twenty years later, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change my damn bathroom sink", the man quoted at the outset blurts out.
According to the workers, for the moment they come mostly retired to check if they get a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before 15 December will also receive half the discount on the February rent.
However, the window of opportunity for "liberalisation" of mining certainly does not dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked for rent in 2011", the window clerk estimates.
In the meantime, RPG proposes on the web and in its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties cannot agree on the rent, an independent judge must settle the matter.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely legal way of acting", warns RPG on its pages.
"Here you are not going to judge anyone", one of the employees of RPG Byty said, and a man standing in the street in front of the customer service center agrees with her, at least in part.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and have 5,000 left for food; I don't have the means to go to court", he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see about that".
"Mr Zaoralek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait", he says.
The rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"Current rentals still do not even cover the amounts needed for the maintenance of the community fund", recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the neglected state of the community fund that annoys the tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for raising the rent.
While in the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments with the rentals, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The big screen hanging from the ceiling, facing the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data highlighted in red.
'The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG's properties.'
'In addition, there will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per square metre per month,' it says on the screen.
Just a 38% increase in rent for 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, it is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 crowns per square metre", says RPG.
At 2,600 flats, the rent will remain unchanged for the next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not affect rentals all at once, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) back into the flats, mainly in savings on heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to people who sign the lease agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need a nursery.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would think that it also hides a small nursery inside with everything that is typical of such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch.Design employees can attend.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose studio produced many well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-nursery.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of a reduced working time, the day care is one of the benefits which Arch.Design offers its workers in the framework of its social programme.
The women in construction and architecture are thus able to combine a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-nursery was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-nursery is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
The funding (an allocation of over CZK 2.8 million) enabled them to buy equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified staff and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), the Arch.Design company is obliged to maintain the mini-nursery with its own funds for three years.
The project took a year to prepare and the Economy Rating company contributed to the submission of the application for funding.
The children are looked after by qualified staff and are cared for by a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education who are present all day long.The nursery currently accommodates children of all ages, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-kindergarten", it can accommodate only a maximum of five children at a time, although with the shifts more come during the day.
The operation of the day care centre is flexible to suit the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the day care centre, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although the curriculum is individual, the contents of the mini-nursery are comparable to the curriculum of the regular preschool.
Children do not just play in it, but they also receive quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach English.
The classroom has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for the children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive atmosphere.
Parents can visit their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when away from their place of work.
So parents are more productive while they work.
Not surprisingly, this naturally creates a relationship of loyalty between the employee and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firms offering a big advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this programme reinforced the marketing of personnel.
The House of Bones still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble a dinosaur's spine, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeletal shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colours, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that recalls the scales and the omnipresent smoothly curved lines, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The front of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and wildlife.
Paying closer attention, you notice a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is enhanced.
The serpentine and twisting forms continue to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood is used for window frames, railings, door ornaments, peepholes, and signs.
Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively commercial street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the remodeling of a house of the year 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, consisting of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his project plans appeared ornaments for the representative apartment of the property owner and the mosaics used in the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and the Güell park of Gaudí, in which other pieces of the same are found.
Because of its organic shape, the locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building conceal religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the era with ventilation fans and typical chimneys.
Its forty-five degree inclination may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not let himself be influenced by them.
However, the building obtained the appropriate permit from the beginning, although evidently the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked with the result that it asked for it to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: only fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner moved into the lower floors.
The living room was on the second floor gallery, and the bedrooms and private part of the apartment were on the third floor.
The ground floor is rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a staircase leading up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudi's reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
Also impressive are Gaudí's play with light, the white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard, and the skylights.
The two-color set brings the maximum amount of light to all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than do dark colors, which in turn absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the list of UNESCO's World Heritage Sites.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most refurbished apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
The visits confirmed, or discovered, that this was a very profitable business and they extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, reaching 16,50 euros, although students, pensioners and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other constructions of Gaudí in the city.
