How to Choose a Mattress and a Bedspread - Women and Men Look for Different Things
Nothing fancy about a bed frame; what really gives a good bed its quality is the surface on which to lie, that is, the mattress and the mattress.
First of all, they must be perfectly complementary so that they are adapted to the specific users.
During the choice, numerous factors come into play, including the owner's weight, height, health status, and sex.
The type of interior in which the mattress and pillow are placed is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cottage that is not usually heated, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat" more slowly.
Furthermore, they are usually considerably heavier than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
It is therefore necessary to turn them over more frequently.
If the central channels are not properly ventilated and are on top of a firm foundation, they keep moisture in.
Customs also play a role in the choice of a bed.
A person who has spent a lot of time abroad will often use a very high mattress with a soft coating and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, harder surface.
"Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn't sleep as well here".
"For their bruised shoulders, heels and hips, they needed mattresses with a soft coating of viscoelastic".
"These mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have nervous system problems, which means they don't get the information from the joints and the skin", explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specialises in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred the viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these appropriate Tempur and the Italians Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico".
You don't have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelasticity anymore.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape based on absorbed heat or adapts to its body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not spin around like after a hard match.
It just makes you sleep better.
The viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of your feet to its height, i.e., between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about six feet will need a bed between six and seven feet.
The minimum width for a single person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
For single rooms, for example single rooms, a minimum of 120-140 cm is recommended.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, a simple rule can be applied to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably curled up towards your elbows", advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert in Czech decorating, who has been dealing with the problem of healthy sleep and furniture ergonomics for many years, a subject she teaches in specialized schools.
In double rooms, each needs his own mattress and bed, so when buying, you have to pay attention to combining the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, the bed pillows will have to be mounted at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, models with springs at least 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softness.
"When touched by hand or when sitting on the mattress, the springs should certainly not be noticeable", warns Helena Prokopová.
Every mattress requires a certain type of mattress.
Fully padded bedrooms, where the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
The mattresses breathe badly and you cannot wash their covers, which is often done today.
And since we sweat between two and three quarts of a liter of sweat every night, it is clear that after about five to seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that talk about a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
But everything has a but.
Therefore, the salesmen give a tip: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, carefully clean and wash the cover, but it is better to add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers are now manufactured with zipper closures throughout their perimeter, so when opening they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavyweight.
In bed, instead of a bedside table, do you have a solid board?
I never will!
At least for beds designed for overnight visitors.
However, it must make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes in the board and must be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft coat.
The polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulating sheet mattresses containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex or sandwich mattresses (e.g. a combination of latex and coconut fibre) may be used, although a mattress with a higher number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the lumbar sheets are reinforced and the rigidity can be adjusted is always preferable.
The jointed sheet pillows should not be used with a spring mattress as it does not react to recline.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
This is a special attachment of the sheets that allows the sheets to be pressed or even tilted so that they perfectly "surround" the shoulders during sleep.
For men with very broad shoulders, this is a very important thing.
Even mattress manufacturers remember them, who, in the "male", began to use a softer zone precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer zone around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are cross- or slab-shaped summers with so-called multi-torsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the voltage is lowered.
You should also note that even if you use the proper mattress and pillow, if you use a bad pillow (large and "mulida"), most of the advantages will be lost.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the corners should only reach the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can be relaxed.
The recommended appropriate size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder-supported pillowcase or the softer part of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers are still increasingly using natural materials or at least mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are in vogue.
The petroleum-based raw materials from which polyurethane foam is made are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soya oil.
In fact, practically all known manufacturers use soya.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin", explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for the microcapsules, which release a fresh scent of forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "cool" themselves with vegetable extracts from the breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs the heat and cools the body, women prefer to "warm" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel more warm.
The current favorites?
Mattresses made from cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various cold foam stiffness and viscoelasticity allows for the manufacture of mattresses of various zones that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns upwards.
Those with a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as healthcare facilities.
The first to obtain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It's hard to save on mattresses and beds.
Sometimes the offers of manufacturers or vendors can be approved, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam attached to the cover for 11,990 kroner.
The second one is free.
The era of viscoelasticity with an open cellular structure and high density began with the "cosmic" material of Tempur.
It was originally developed as a NASA material because during take-off, astronauts were subjected to enormous overload.
Tempur melts with heat and hardens with cold.
Thus, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and adapts optimally to its pressure.
It is therefore ideal for preventing sores, but also for improving comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
The domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C foam or Twinsaver and similar.
More and more parents are using people-tracking devices to monitor their children.
Fear for their children is leading more and more people to think about monitoring them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also track the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, to the case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At present the device is about the size of a matchbox, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and started to find out about the means available to better protect her children.
Even at the cost of invading her privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that this is not spying, but another means of reducing the chances of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I recognize that in certain cases, such devices can be misused, for example, by getting into someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases".
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons", adds Pilin.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if the child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
"Even young children are very creative in deliberately losing things to avoid being controlled".
"Parents used to rely on mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device", says Bočková.
In his view, it is debatable whether such a device is really useful in case of an attack.
"If it is a planned kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check to see if the child is carrying any kind of electronic device that might reveal their location".
"Now it's the phone".
"As the use of tracking devices spreads, so will they, as their sale will undoubtedly be done with much publicity".
"In such cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of a makeshift attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, their presence can be helpful.
'The device may be configured to regularly send the position after a specified period.'
"If you suffer damage, at least you will facilitate the last position of the person in question".
"The most expensive devices have a built-in tiltmeter, so if the person simply slips and stands still, the device will immediately give a warning with the position in question", says Čech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with mobile smartphones with navigation, on which only special software must be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices that are about the size of a matchbook or the smaller size of mobile phones.
So you can get lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, for that reason, tests are currently being conducted with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device".
"Or that it identifies him after a certain time, which can buy time for the police", he adds.
Although the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hung up, they will still use the same technology as used for vehicle tracking.
This is the verification of the position with a GPS system (used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough flares to surround the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech Army bought 277 miles of fuse to ignite explosives.
Last year the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of mecha to its arsenal.
So they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the wick is two years, four at the most.
The army bought the explosive wick from the STV Group, a. s. for forty million crowns.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of mecha saying that the soldiers need for the training maneuvers 60 kilometers of mecha a year.
According to the calculations of the army pyrotechnicians, with whom MF DNES got in touch, it is decided however that, in such a case, all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners should also perform such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year.
They did not want exemptions nor did Minister of Defense Alexandr Vondr and Army Captain Vlastimil Picek.
Only then could the army justify spending 60 kilometers of mecha.
That length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough supplies for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of mecha, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade recently complained personally to Minister Vondra because they say they have hardly any ammunition for various weapons, so they are limited even to shooting practices for money.
And let's not even talk about the lack of underwear.
"I can't understand why we are bought such quantities of wick repeatedly".
"But it's their decision and they'll definitely know why they're acting like this".
"For us, the army is a good customer whom we, as a company, try to satisfy", admits the commercial director of STV Group, Jan Děcký.
Ministry of Defence spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of mecha also saying that he will have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký of STV Group indicates that the wick has a lifespan of only four years and, in the case of military or police pyrotechnic products, two years.
"If it is stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four years", says one of the soldiers who, because of possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its service life, each round must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometres of wick, it obtained a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's order of 244 kilometers", says Pejšek, spokesman for the Ministry of Defense's purchasing center.
For comparison's sake, the annual consumption of firewood by police firemen, who remove the ammunition from World War II or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
Furthermore, the police always ask only the right amount to use up the ammunition before its useful life is over.
It was decided for reasons of safety for the pyrotechnics and, in addition, in the meantime more modern and reliable types of firework can be obtained.
The Ministry is already having clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tonnes of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the Czechoslovak army of 200,000 was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: hundreds of kilometers of old mecha will have to be removed, which is now being bought "cheaply".
I still live off the contacts I made through the contest.
Winning the Entrepreneur of the Year competition helped Lukáš Pytloun in selling his hotel franchise.
The last edition, the contest "Entrepreneur of the year" won the 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukáš Pytloun from Liberec.
His success story seems to be taken out of a movie.
Lukáš Pytloun was a man who loved to travel.
Abroad he realised that in Liberec he needed quality accommodation at a good price.
With the savings he had made from seasonal jobs abroad and a bank loan, he bought a five-story, half-ruined house.
Considering that he was still in his third year of college, he was really brave.
"The quality-price ratio of accommodation in our area has now prompted me to do something about it", says Lukáš Pytloun.
He started renting the first floor that was rebuilt to foreign workers.
All the income he earned he reinvested back into the building, which he gradually turned into a 54-room boarding house.
Since then, in seven years in the business, he managed to gradually open in Liberec four pensions, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of around 300 in all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of all was, until recently, the four-star design hotel Pytloun.
However, this year it opened another one of the same quality.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov or Tisé, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise", said the number one entrepreneur last year.
"The fact that we won the 'Entrepreneur of the year' competition helped a lot with this sale of hotel licences", adds the grateful Pytloun.
The victory increased his fame and popularity both in Liberec and in the surrounding area.
"People recognized me on the street, still often congratulated me and, I must say, it was very nice", she recalls.
He would certainly recommend any company that wants to try out to enter the competition.
But he feels that it is not necessary to win, but that participation is already beneficial.
He claims that, so far, he is still living off of the contacts and acquaintances that, without the competition, he might not have obtained.
"Some people I met thanks to the contest I have started to collaborate habitually".
The fame associated with success, in his view, also included in the employees,
In total, about seventy.
"I have seen them show greater loyalty and are proud to be a part of something that gained general recognition".
"It is not, by any means, my own personal success, but it is the result of the hard work of the whole team".
"It's just that my name is on the front page", says Lukáš Pytloun modestly today.
I wish my successor a year more peaceful than we had in Farmet
The euphoria of victory was soon dissipated by the impact of the crisis.
Thanks to the hard work of the victor, it's possible that Farmet has already gotten over the worst.
The owner of the Farmet company, Karel Žďárský, was awarded the first prize in the latest edition of the Vodafone "Company of the Year" competition last year at the "Slavic House" in Prague.
The jury appreciated his efforts, with which he managed to turn a small technical workshop in Česká Skalice into a firm with a turnover of hundreds of millions.
"I can say that the award has not only encouraged me but all my collaborators and improved our confidence to fight against the competition", says the winner of last year.
The story of Farmet begins with the desire to do something useful.
So when the state offered Karel Žďárský's father the rent of a small workshop as compensation for the seizure of property during communism, she did not hesitate too much; she resigned from her position in the company where she worked and, with a couple of colleagues, founded the company with her father of plastic batteries.
Soon after, they began specializing in vegetable oil presses.
Eight years later they became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in central Europe.
They also gained a greater presence among the general public after success in the media competition.
"Not only did our customers start to see the Farmet brand as considerably better, but also the foreign partners started to value the collaboration with a company that was more successful in their country", says Karel Žďárský.
Last year, perhaps, it was not just a display of victory euphoria in Farmet.
It also received recognition for the business results up to 2008 and partially 2009.
