A survey that reveals the ridiculous rules
The Absurdity of the Year poll is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
He's already managed to eliminate some ridiculous regulations.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdez survey of the year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was adopted by more than a third of the nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the Social Security Administration asked for an extract from the Trade Register, although its officials can obtain it with two moves of the mouse.
Thanks to the poll, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the commercial register when it conducts a check on the insured's taxes", said Jana Buraňová, a spokeswoman for ČSSZ.
The aim of the absurdity survey of the year is to find out what rules and regulations companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those which are absurd.
This year it is taking part in the business tournament of the Hospodářské noviny publication for the fourth time and is also starting to attract interest from the general public.
While last year's edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it practically reached four thousand.
And it's not surprising, because we still have a lot of legal obligations that we have to meet just to trade.
"Perhaps in the number of documents required for tax return we are first in the world", says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, the simplification of business rules has been a stated objective of all governments.
However, in comparison with the rest of the world, the situation is improving, especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic is in 74th place in the ranking of the conditions for starting a business, eight places lower than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was first held in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can point to some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the competition closes.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. Afterwards, the competition organizer chooses seven candidates for the "pre-prize" and during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The absurdity that gets the most votes wins.
For this year's survey, over a hundred rules and regulations were submitted, including 105 that don't make sense.
The examples were sent by businessmen, professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of the 70 proposals for this year is published on the competition pages.
The announcement of the competition, which is always held at the beginning of November in Prague's Wenceslas Square, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world usually participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium-Sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, and Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic, attended the competition.
"Economic prosperity cannot be maintained if the state continually imposes obstacles on entrepreneurs, so my aim is to eliminate every year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade", announced Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate the absurd regulations do not end in drunken waters.
In 2007, what most bothered people was the obligation of the employer to inform three days in advance the business office in the permanent operating zone of his intention to attend a fair or exhibition with a stand.
This obligation was abolished in the new industrial law.
The requirement that came second in number of votes in 2007, i.e. the reporting to the labour office by their foreign workers of business trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the so-called green card law.
And the third one is the winner.
The absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their office a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
So this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the requirement to have a refrigerator.
A new category recognises socially responsible companies
Environmental, humanitarian, educational or sporting projects are valued.
The novelty of this fifth edition of the Hospodářské noviny competition is the category called Responsible Business of the Year 2010.
