Families will have to pay an additional cost of several hundred crowns a month.
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to withdraw several hundred more crowns from their portfolios each month from January onwards.
Electricity prices rise by 4.6%, gas prices by around 2%, some cities will have to pay up to 10% more for water supplies and many cities are also increasing the price of central heating.
The electricity bill for families living in apartments should be about 100 krona more per year than now.
However, the main electricity suppliers reduced prices, due to increasing support for the production of energy from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaic.
However, gas becomes moderately more expensive, especially at the time when heating is used most and therefore consumption is highest.
In this case, they must also have a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are getting more expensive all over the country, the change in the price of central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the larger municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay from January onwards about 50 krona more per month for central heating, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 krona extra per year.
Prague residents will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the infrastructure rent.
If the rent does not change, the Prague residents will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the country.
In Northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
Rental prices for 450,000 rented flats in Prague, where the regulation will end in January, may increase considerably.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns about 2,500 flats in Ústí nad Labem, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take to court anyone who doesn't agree with the new lease.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of about 300,000 flats, could rise next year by as much as 10%.
Young Czechs get drunk on Fernet and rum.
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to get over a hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors encountering such cases in the hospital's paediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because they take a long time to get drunk".
"Hard drinks are the new trend", Luděk Pelikán, head of pediatrics at the Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, told Právo.
"When they manage to grab a bottle from their father's pantry, it can be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka".
"The vodka has the advantage that it lighten with juice and that it doesn't smell as bad", he explains.
This was also confirmed by the spokeswoman of the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Usually, it's either Fernet or rum".
"That's the modern alcoholic beverage, particularly among schoolchildren".
"In some cases, they use home-made spirit", adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelican, it's 13- and 14-year-old drinkers who usually show up at hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in the pediatrics department in Motol, where ambulances brought young people from nearby areas.
"One girl had to go in maybe four times".
"It started at the age of 12, when she was brought in with 3.5 of alcohol in her blood, plus a mixture with ecstasy", says the department doctor about this case.
"I was at the fair in Holešovice at some dance party".
"What's interesting is that her mother wasn't even surprised that her daughter was gone for 48 hours", the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of parental interest or even their clear tolerance of drinking by their children that is considered to be the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts say that in the case of children, it is not really a question of dependence.
"Alcoholic is defined as a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the associated phenomena, which does not occur in children".
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is more likely due to a systematically failed social or family environment", explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, this year in the pediatric clinic in Motol, forty drunk children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, statistics only show those who come in with severe intoxication and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after a routine medical examination, go home with their parents or the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink brandy, for Pelican there are three seasonal highs and lows to mention: Halloween, New Year's Eve, and the end of the school year.
"In such a situation, they drink for bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays".
"On Halloween I have seen up to seven drunken children at once", adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under medical supervision paradoxically have the advantage of not suffering a terrible hangover at home the next day.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by the injection of a serum with glucose and nutrients that the body lacks.
"These people are much better off because after a hectic night, they get up and don't feel any pain".
"They just get confused about where they are", says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose their good humor at least when they see the expenses they have incurred.
Transport by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients can cost tens of thousands of crowns.
"I have often used cost as a means of education, when I tell the children directly on the visit how much their drinking has cost them and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job in order for you to earn enough to pay for that night", adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in your opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft are found for the first time in foreign hands in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defence replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, left Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the aircraft Casa - EADS is located.
It is the first time that a device of this type has been found in the hands of someone other than the Czech army.
At the moment, they were only abroad for training or demonstration flights.
It is the two-seater version L-159T1, which until the moment used the Czech army and was still in flying condition.
The remaining three aircraft are the L-159 single-seaters.
These are still held by Aer Vodochody and the intermediary for the sale, the company Omnipol, took them over last week.
Jan Peješk from the defense press department indicates that it is not yet known when the planes will be physically removed from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seaters, on the other hand, were separated from the long-repaired aircraft, without any additional investment or contribution from the Ministry".
'The L-159T1 two-seaters were exchanged in their present state,' he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army is not without two-seater aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed with Aer Vodochody a contract for an amount of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary devices L-159 for two-seaters.
One of the new planes was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS was committed to the planes being added to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly states that EADS is the company that is withdrawing the L-159 aircraft and that they will be used for pilot training from NATO countries".
'It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how he will use them in this context,' says Pejšek.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published prematurely that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in L-159s.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.500 million crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call for a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense leadership claims that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159s abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24 of them, so they want to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already brought a case before the European Court of Justice against the Czech Ministry of Defence for choosing aircraft by a European tender rather than by contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the last one should arrive at Prague's Kbely airport in 14 days.
A longer index finger than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men with a longer index than the annular are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer journal.
It could depend on your testosterone levels, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that relative finger length may be a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men up to 60 years of age", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could therefore help determine which men should be screened for prostate cancer, particularly if this trait is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, Eeles says.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and simultaneously 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They had the same odds of getting prostate cancer as the 19% of those with the same length of fingers.
For men with an index finger longer than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under the age of 60 the reduction reached 87%.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The senior Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he is aware of the study, but does not think that the link between finger length and cancer can be "fully demonstrated".
