In the weeks since losing her husband, Cristina Fernández, the president of Argentina, has enjoyed a great deal of public sympathy that has increased her popularity by 20 points to over 50%, the highest level she has recorded since her election in 2007.
However, whether she can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year's elections will depend on whether the clearly affected Mrs Fernández leaves aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are inconclusive.
Mr Kirchner, who continued to take charge of economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had a habit of making budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra income at their discretion.
In theory, Ms Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened since Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissenting members of the ruling Peronist movement have confronted Ms. Fernández.
However, after a chaotic session in which one deputy punched another in the face and other deputies accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue", said the president.
The 2010 budget will therefore be carried over to next year, giving the President even more leeway to spend it.
The economy is improving considerably: it's likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but numerous private calculations, in addition to the union wage demands, put it at close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, he put pressure on the private sector and he had INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt the official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernandez now moderate these policies?
He's called meetings between the private sector and the union leaders.
In addition, officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by high prices of Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the growth boost achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Mrs Fernandez is giving signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial links with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with the bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it seems that Mrs Fernandez is about to conclude an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Club of Paris, to which she owes some 6,700 million dollars.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this would not involve the IMF's supervision, as is usually the case.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer "technical assistance" to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems to be the prelude to the cleanup of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether President Fernandez wants to continue in politics when her term ends, given that she no longer has her husband at her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has grown tired of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentinians return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have subsided.
If she wants to win another election, she'll have to decide whether or not to repudiate, with a calm voice, many of her husband's policies.
Halfway to China
Taiwan's voters are slowly moving towards a kind of closer union with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70% of those eligible, turned out on November 27 to elect mayors and councillors of five urban districts in what appears to be a wide-ranging assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr Ma himself has become a champion of the continent's feelings, forging innovative business ties, including a partial free trade pact, the biggest change in relations with China since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but by a narrow margin.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party ended up winning three of the five mayoral elections, it failed to get a majority of the votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (PPD), which has been leaning towards full independence for Taiwan, won practically 50% of all votes against 45% for the KMT.
If it had been the presidential election, Mr. Ma would have been in trouble.
Since his election two years ago, his party's vote share has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the PPD tied with the KMT in the city council.
The election featured the typical elements of Taiwanese elections, including noisy campaign trucks and large crowds with banners and light-clothed girls dancing.
Nor was the mysterious attempted murder of rigor.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan, honorary chairman of the KMT, was campaigning for one of the KMT candidates the night before the election.
A man in the crowd shot the young man directly in the face, wounding him and killing a passerby.
The curious thing is that it has not been possible to determine whether the man intended to harm Lien or to take revenge on the candidate.
In any case, says Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PPD, the shooting affected the elections, sowing suspicion about the PPD and causing voters to lean towards the KMT.
Perhaps the only big winner of the campaign was China.
It was surprising that the issue was not the continent itself.
Instead, the candidates talked about public housing plans and job creation.
Taiwan normally enjoys its de facto independence and detests the military threat from China.
As a result, the KMT usually avoids publicising its links to the government in Beijing.
But this time too the PDP avoided stirring up anti-China sentiment.
It responds to the new awareness that Chinese trade is essential for Taiwan's economic survival.
For his part, Mr Ma claimed that it had been confirmed that his policy towards China was acceptable to the majority of Taiwanese.
The Beijing government is expected to continue to bribe them with trade, in line with its strategy to get Taiwan back into the fold.
China wasted no time sending a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
It would also like to see political integration, but first things first.
It's best to wait until after the 2012 presidential election to do so.
In any case, the PPD has reinvented itself.
Two years ago, it was in a bad situation: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was imprisoned on corruption charges.
President between 2000 and 2008, he openly encouraged explicit independence.
However, under Ms. Tsai's leadership, a new generation of moderates has emerged and the PPD is making efforts to attract professionals and youth.
Ms. Tsai has been welcomed as the PDP's presidential candidate, as has Ms. Su Tseng-chang, who served under Chen.
Now his party is doing everything possible to show that it can also have relations with Beijing.
Mrs Tsai announced plans to set up an expert group to act as a point of contact between the PPD and China, provided that negotiations could take place without preconditions.
Ms. Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party represents a "reliable alternative" to Mr. Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems furious about the change.
In a statement issued from his jail cell, he claimed that the PPD candidates would have fared better if they had insisted that Taiwan was an independent country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatist, not to run for president.
Even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the PPD will have a hard time choosing among their potential candidates.
The KMT must also make an examination of conscience.
Mr. Ma's ratings have been poor, despite impressive economic growth; KMT candidates have not wanted to campaign with him.
Its lack of popularity seems to be due mainly to unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman claims that he will restructure his cabinet as well as local teams.
Large samples of the DPP suggest that Taiwan's support for a rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese consider economic integration with China to be inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a well-known columnist, "the point of no return has already been crossed".
Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is the surprise choice in the category of breakthrough artist.
Act at the request of a president and people will probably notice you.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer personally selected by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, was one of the surprise winners of this year's Grammys with a high-profile nomination in the Best New Artist category.
Considering that Spalding has been a highly acclaimed jazz figure since his 2008 album, "Esperanza", the nomination is thought-provoking, but it respects the Grammys' rules that an artist must not have released more than three albums before recording the one that "determines the public identity of that artist".
Her ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", was certainly a breakthrough, and given her light and pleasing vocal style, as well as a great ability with pop, funk and Latin rhythms influences, one can at least draw a distinction between Spalding and the path to Norah Jones' 2003 hit, the closest equivalent for voters of the Grammys, who have lately concentrated on the jazz realm for this category.
In the remaining categories, Grammy voters rightfully honored "Historicity" by the Vijay Iyer Trio, a thrilling and magnificent record that was a favorite last year.
Among Iyer's competitors are veteran saxophonist James Moody with "Moody 4B" and keyboardist John Beasley for "Positootly".
Trombone Shorty, a favorite New Orleans striker and regular guest on HBO's "Treme", was honored in the contemporary jazz category, which otherwise leans considerably toward fusion as on albums by Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Darcy James Argue's wild punk band Secret Society earned a well-deserved spot in the big band category, competing against the great chamber jazz of the Billy Childs Ensemble and the always risky Dave Holland, whose live album with its octet, "Pathways", was a great example of the bassist's democratic leadership in his band.
Grammy nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey for best direction of classical albums
The classical music nominations for the 53rd Grammy Awards include a mixture of musicians and songwriters from around the world.
The top nominations went to Michael Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", for piano and orchestra, five movements, and Steve Mackey with "Dreamhouse", a work for eclectic orchestra in three movements.
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California are Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a piece commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and premiered at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also nominated for his Mandolin Concerto.
The classical music nominations are distributed in thirteen categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo albums.
The category for Classic Producer of the Year includes five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin, and James Mallinson.
The nominees for the classical music album are Bruckner for Symphonies No. 3 and No. 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey for "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" by various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg for "Lulu" by the orchestra of the Royal Opera House; Adolf Hasse for "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho for "L'Amour de Loin" by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the orchestra and choir of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan for "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
Composers nominated for a Grammy for contemporary compositions include Pärt for the Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti", and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a session recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The piece, about 30 minutes long, is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil magnate Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" is nominated for solo instrumental performance with orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin player Avi Avital, who performed the concerto with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"I composed it with sounds from the Middle East and numerous scales and rhythms from North Africa", Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Director Pierre Boulez, 85, was nominated in the orchestral performance category for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra during a recording of Stravinsky's works.
The instrumental soloists nominated include the pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; the organist Paul Jacobs; the violinist Julia Fischer; and the harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
The nominees as vocal soloists are all women this year: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical mix category, soprano Jessye Norman was nominated for her recording of "Roots - My Life, My Song".
Proposed Temecula mosque gets approval from the planning commission
The mosque project for Temecula has won the unanimous support of the local planning commission after more than five hours of often heated public testimony.
Critics attacked the project as promoting terrorism and traffic jams.
However, the committee members decided on Wednesday night that the new religious center respected local law and would be aesthetically impressive.
"Many good people came to show their support, whether Christians or Jews or Baha'is, from all religions", said Hadi Nael, president of the Islamic center of the Temecula Valley, on Thursday morning.
"The truth is, as an American citizen, I am proud of it".
"It proves that justice prevails".
"The opposition is really minimal", he adds.
"They just talk too loudly".
"There are wonderful people in this valley".
The meeting began at 6 p.m. and lasted until almost midnight; most of the time was spent with people who were advocating for or against the center, about the same number on each side, according to the Press-Enterprise.
The debate continued on the newspaper's website.
"America no longer exists", reads one of the comments.
"This is another Planet of the Apes with Lady Liberty dead in the sand".
"America has fallen".
Plans to build Islamic centers have sparked protests in other parts of the country as well, including near the ground zero, the New York area where the September 11, 2011 attacks occurred.
In the Valley of Temecula, Imam Mahmoud Harmoush has reported acts of violence.
His congregation of about 135 families had been living together without problems in Riverside County for years, but he wanted a larger and better space than the warehouse he rented on a shared property with a manufacturer of water filtration systems.
The new 24,943 square foot mosque, with a Mediterranean architectural style, would include two minarets and rise to 43 feet.
