A resistant microbe to arsenic raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients widens the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers discovered the curious bacterium here on Earth, they say it proves that life may be possible without the major elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity".
"It can grow on either phosphorus or arsenic".
"That makes it very peculiar, though it is close to being a truly 'alien' type of life form", said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time, it was thought that there were six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacterium, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible", said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
Anbar said the find is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, as researchers need to be able to recognize life, know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the convening of a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a great speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to power their biochemistry and that the set of 'standard' elements we consider essential for life may not be as fixed", said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't part of the investigation team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", added Cockell.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute for Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could substitute for one another.
"Arsenic is toxic primarily because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate between them".
"However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it gets in and, in a way, it stunts the biochemical machinery", explains Anbar.
The researchers took the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, to which they were able to adapt and use to grow.
The microbe grows best on phosphorus, but the fact that it can live on arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life that uses arsenic may naturally exist, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but that no example has ever been found that works.
Arsenic was more common in the earliest ages of Earth, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
"It does suggest that there could be other ways of generating life, not just the way life formed on Earth in ancient times", said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
The missing stolen dogs from Compton have been found.
The two missing dogs from the four that were stolen have been found outside the Bellflower Motel, Los Angeles County Sheriff's deputies said Thursday.
The four competition dogs, two Akitas and two Welsh Pembroke Corgis, were reported missing Tuesday when someone stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express van they were spending the night in, outside the Bellflower Motel 6, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the remaining two were found late Wednesday night, according to Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
"The good news is that the dogs are doing well", said Whitmore.
"They're in good shape".
"They have returned to their rightful owners".
Whitmore would not say exactly where the dogs were found, in what neighborhood, or the circumstances of the discovery.
"An investigation is underway".
"We don't want to say anything", said Whitmore.
"We're following some leads".
The owners of the dogs, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, could not be reached for comment Thursday.
They met with their two Akitas at an animal shelter in Downey County on Wednesday afternoon.
Sheriff's deputies found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
According to the authorities, the Akitas (Trace, a 3-year-old dog, and Didi, a 10-month-old dog) had not been harmed.
But Bunny and Peter, the Corgis that Rickard and Peek were planning to show off at the local dog show this week on behalf of the Japanese dog owners, were still missing as of Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were in town for the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach this weekend and they were intending to show off Trace.
The other dogs were to be exhibited in other competitions scheduled for the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba championship, Peek told The Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops on the couple's almost two-month tour of dog races.
Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They usually stay in motels and park the van right outside their bedroom window.
They were carrying three other dogs (a boxer cub, a Parson Russell terrier, and a Brittany, who slept with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and the Corgis in the van because they have very thick fur and would be fresher.
They left the windows slightly open so that the dogs could breathe fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the van stolen Tuesday morning at 6:00 a.m.
Peek had said they would offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the Corgis, equipped with microchips to identify them.
Thursday, it was unclear whether a reward would be given or not.
The lion is ready to roar again, as the MGM restructuring gets final court approval.
After 18 months of confusion and uncertainty, MGM has finally got the green light to start over.
On Thursday, a New York federal bankruptcy judge officially approved the plan "pre-armed" by creditors to wipe out approximately $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and premiering movies and television shows.
Thursday's ruling confirms that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, so there are no further legal obstacles to MGM relaunching under Spyglass Entertainment founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the chief executives of what will be a scaled-down studio.
The staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320 members.
In fact, MGM won't even get out of Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a planned $500 million credit facility to fund the operations and production of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating the loan, which is itself contributing $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The firm's restructuring process began in May 2009, when investment bank Moelis and Co. was hired to provide management advice needed to put its finances in order, while it struggled to make interest payments of $300 million a year.
In August, Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron Chairman and bankruptcy recovery expert known for his work on Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial woes and satisfy the studio's more than 140 creditors required much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed to put the company up for sale in late 2009.
However, the auction attracted few bidders and none willing to pay the more than $2 billion that the creditors were looking for.
By spring of this year, he was back at the drawing board as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan that, after months of debate and internal disagreements, was finally backed by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially emerges from bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper's companies will receive multimillion-dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will get a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which have been collecting $375,000 a month for their company management services, will receive a "success fee" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which released only one film this year, and has assembled an annual slate of seven or eight films set to come out in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", along with Warner Bros.
The studio needs to take out a separate loan of between $265 and $275 million to fund its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM's debt, had been trying to arrange a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent talks between the two companies did not result in an agreement.
Tech Toys wants to balance its gift budget
While the iPad is the leading contender to be this year's most wonderful toy, followed by, perhaps, the Microsoft Kinect gaming system, both can mean a significant dent in your gift budget.
Consider that for the price of an iPad, you can buy five BMX bikes for $99 each, and a Kinect game costs the same as 10 classic jump ropes adorned with beads, or about 48 cans of Play-Doh.
But there are ways to balance your gift budget.
I recently visited three national toy stores, Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us and BJ's Wholesale Club, to see what electronic toys I could buy for under $80.
It was immediately clear that Moore's Law has been working; this year's tech toy will probably have more power, cost the same and even a little less compared to last year's.
Also, while there are generally fewer new toys with associated websites, two of the best known of these, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offerings.
And button-battery-powered toys are on the rise, as are toys with rechargeable batteries.
Here are some recommendations.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us unless otherwise noted.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13, for 3 years and up) are stuffed toys the size of guinea pigs that sing a note when their bellies are clenched.
One squeeze equals a note, and a second squeeze begins to make a song.
If you buy more than one, they'll sing in harmony.
Caution: Once you start to squeeze, you can't stop.
For singing combined with dancing, Dance Star Mickey (Fisher-Price, $60, for 2 years and up) is the best choice.
Borrowing from last year's Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic dummy plays turn-switching games like Simom Dice, and can do the moonwalk, thanks to its innovative articulated wheeled feet with locking device.
The children who tested the toy used Mickey as a dance instructor, though their parents complained about the lack of a volume control.
If you're a child of the '80s, you may remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
He has returned (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, for 3 years and up), with a backpack full of question cards designed to turn a car ride into a session with a self-correcting exercise book.
If you are reluctant to give your child a smartphone, here are three independent alternatives.
VTech's MobiGo ($60, 3-8 years) is the cheapest and easiest to use, featuring a qwerty keyboard; although the games don't teach as effectively as the Leapster Explorer ($70, 3-8 years), it is the first major upgrade in the Leapster line, with a newer, brighter display.
Neither version is compatible with the old cartridges.
Fisher-Price's iXL ($90 for 3-7 years) uses an iTunes-like system to present games and e-books, and has an SD card slot that allows viewing family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30 Hasbro, for 8 and up) is a game of five blocks barely bigger than a matchbox, each with its own LED display.
The goal is to put words together by putting the blocks in a row before time runs out; it's formidable for an impromptu word-making competition.
More and more toys are having some kind of online connection.
Based on their presence in toy stores alone, the two biggest are Webkinz and Club Penguin.
To buy your child a pet online at Club Penguin, for example, you can get a Disney Club Penguin 2" Mix 'N Match Figure Pack, ($5, 6 to 12 years old) that includes a coin with a hidden code.
When you redeem the code online, your child gets enough credit at the Club Penguin store for two items.
These could include roller skates on wheels or a pet Puffle toy.
Slightly larger than the piggyback on your toothbrush, the Hexbug Nano ($10, for 5 years and older) is the latest in a line of button-battery-powered microrobots.
The fake insect moves rapidly on 12 vibrating silicone legs in random directions.
It's fun to make a maze of blocks to see if you can find the way out.
It's also durable.
Ours was able to leave the kitchen table and even spend a while inside our dog's mouth.
A more moderate side of policing is promoted in China
As an urban drill sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the step in a town square, sternly inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of the chengguan, China's stout urban police, feared and despised for their capricious forceful measures and their penchant for violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of onlookers.
"Signed it!"
"Watch out!"
Show them, he whispered, "how pretty the girls are!"
Four girls barely past their teens with identical white gloves and olive-green jackets and tight-fitting trousers to attract attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats, perfectly placed on top of the hair tied with blue and white striped bow ties.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance", said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"Models are cute".
More than one government has tried to clean up China's urban inspectors.
One city mandated that all new recruits have a college degree.
Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: In 2009, according to one report, 50 officers surrounded a rogue snack cart, and watched it with a constant frown for half an hour, until the street vendor collected his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough cop a softer, more feminine side.
Sadly, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to raise China's paltry respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are authorized only to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, Hubei Province inspectors beat a passerby to death after he used his cell phone to film them while they dissolved a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted online, which described how to effectively whip criminals without making them bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon peddler suffered brain damage after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on the government", lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another tactical controversy.
The newspaper called for "a really thorough cleaning".
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district issued a notice for eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News wondered if the women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a little of both.
The district advertisement called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure "and the five facial features of harmony".
They had to be above average height, over 5 feet, 5 1/2 inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officials said the work was physically too strenuous for women over 25.
"Your image is the important thing", an unnamed district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the candidates' external qualities will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc".
Then comes temperament "and the qualities within".
Women Chengguan are like florists, he said, adding, "besides being florists, they will have other responsibilities".
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district's city administration office, is not eager to back that description.
But she noted that height requirements were standard in many Chinese job advertisements for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
Whether this means being handsome is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely the handicapped or disfigured should not be introduced.
"We cannot allow a lame person or a hunchback to come to work here", Mr. Zheng said.
"His image would not be good".
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old, with her colorful cheeks and a subtly curved mouth.
She doesn't think the accent in her look is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asked with a sardonic look.
His fellow worker with dimples, Xu Yang, 21, said, "Our work should present the image of the city".
They are also not opposed to their time-limited work, they said, because they harbor greater career ambitions than simply chasing salesmen off the back roads where they are supposed to do business.
