Can civility bridge the divides?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a little civility has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a swift return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the big issues that should be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion of the differences between the two sides, as well as an acknowledgement of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to gain partisan points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the chairman's deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a testing period, probing each other for signs of cooperativism and compromise, as they try to gauge the limits of public opinion and voter patience for renewed partisan warfare.
That is why the meeting on Tuesday and the subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change of climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, spending, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no question that things have changed with regard to the way things are said", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"They are inevitable after the election.
Elections stir up partisan passions, which then go out.
That's good".
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda for the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and nobody's in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a compromise to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make it seem like they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits for the unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is increased optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START nuclear disarmament pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues in the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said that the beginning of a period of disagreement was very likely and even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, psychology will revert the situation to one of confrontation in the short term", he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to genuine cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012", he said.
The motives have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of overstating their position, they know they must try to deliver on their promises to cut state spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own estimation, have forced the deficit issue onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they've been struggling to get anywhere near that number.
The biggest resistance is among elected officials on the panel, suggesting that on tax issues there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans in the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama over the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as it did in 1995, then both parties will watch closely for the reaction of the people.
Whoever they consider to be losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as merely the prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Leaked US document portrays Moscow as a corruption haven
The city is controlled by a "cleptocracy", and it leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money it collects directly to the Kremlin, the US Embassy in Russia reported in February.
Both the police and the Federal Security Service were reported to operate huge blackmail schemes, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized crime groups.
Each layer of the bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical authority", takes its share as money climbs the ladder.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and it blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a clean-up since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have systematically denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won several libel suits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian TV channel about a documentary that suggested he was corrupt, he claimed: "It's crazy, it's bullshit, it's a nuisance".
According to polls, Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it's unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it's unheard of for diplomats from a foreign country to do that.
"The Moscow city government's direct links to criminality have led some to call it 'dysfunctional,' and to claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government", the note states.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a term from the criminal and mafia world that literally means 'roof' or protection) that permeates the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor's office, as well as all sectors of the Moscow city government bureaucracy.
"Analysts identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow".
"Luzhkov is on top".
"The SFS, MVD and militia are on the second level".
"Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level".
"This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas, because the city doesn't provide some services".
The report claims that the SFS collects money from the largest companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report stated, "explained that Moscow business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than the criminal groups, but are also protected by the law".
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority".
The note notes that while the collection of money is complete, protection may be patchy; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay promptly find their businesses shut down on one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to rely on bureaucrats", Georgy Satarov, director of the Moscow-based Indem think tank, said in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy".
"He doesn't belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia".
Without politics, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
Nationwide, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked from least to most corrupt).
The revelation of the US Embassy memo, which did not occur until late night Moscow time, is sure to cause upset within the Russian government, and although Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow's weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that the WikiLeaks documents might be lies and reacted angrily to a revelation that claimed that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic politics in this country", he said.
"But to be honest with you, we didn't suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would be done in such an immoral way".
The Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom, with walls stained and peeled, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School remembered the man who had built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok".
"He was a good leader and he cared about his people", said Mr. Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront those who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook here that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a mixed UN-Cambodian court handed down the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the Anlong Veng Khmer Rouge veterans, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they can't do anything", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil".
"This is creating divisions within families".
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died from hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the Khmer Rouge's most senior fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their arms, the rank-and-file soldiers remained poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have gotten little benefit after the surrender", said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have embodied the regime's utopian agrarian ideology".
"They were raised with no concept of doing business".
Lim Sor, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Khmer Rouge was good", he said.
"Ta Mok fed the whole family".
"But now life is hard because we have to provide for ourselves".
The current Khmer Rouge court has also caused concern here.
Early next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the top leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it hasn't said whether it will pursue cases beyond those four.
This did little to allay fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told investigators at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are thought to have died.
On a recent sullen afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden stilts on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the parched grass, Im Chaem refused to speak of her Khmer Rouge past.
She claimed that if the court summoned her, she would not appear.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable", he stated.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, though experts and historians question this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past", he said.
But facing the past is precisely what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation centre.
"Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is putting the broken pieces back together", he said.
"It is our obligation to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand".
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", 75 pages long.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's secondary school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's link to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng Secondary School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But her parents reacted skeptically when she brought the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court", he said.
"They are suspicious because they are not sure about how many people the court will prosecute".
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path with too much weed and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a black soot rectangle covered by a rusted tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside cell phone salesman, said he didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray to him", she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day she decided to walk to the final resting place of Pol Pot, where she would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in hopes of good luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its stockpile of weapons-grade uranium
In a surprise victory for President Obama's campaign to protect nuclear material worldwide, the government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it will give up its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement released after Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov on the sidelines of a security summit.
For years, the U.S. government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and it seemed they had reached a point of no return last spring.
But US officials told the Washington Post that a pair of classified operations were carried out with Belarus in the last two months, to retrieve 84.82 kg of weapons-grade uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
This set the stage for Wednesday's agreement to remove the rest of the material, about 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke on condition of anonymity because of the confidentiality of the subject.
The agreement appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the Obama-chaired 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit in April, which excluded Belarus.
And apparently it was a good achievement to secure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a seat at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit".
"This shows that this process is working", said Ken Luongo, president of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear safety.
Clinton said the deal is "a very significant and important step" by Belarus.
In April 2009 Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide for the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did it under the George W. Bush administration.
At the time of Obama's Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had declared that the nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have preserved highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what is basically weapons-grade uranium) and low-enriched uranium", Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material... we will not manufacture dirty bombs, and we will not sell them to anyone".
"We use it for research purposes, that's all".
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating interest in reaching a deal.
Officials claimed that the first task of removing uranium from Belarus, in October, was particularly complicated, as the material had been lightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded onto a special train that traveled over 2,000 km to a Russian facility for storage and disposal.
According to officials, the second operation ended on Monday and was done by air.
The U.S. government spent $13 million on the tasks, and most of the money was used to supply Belarus with the research facility for low-enriched uranium, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an official at the Department of Energy who works on Global Threat Reduction, said that "this was coordinated and orchestrated very carefully to build the trust" that led to the deal signed by Clinton.
The James Martin Center for Nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus possessed at least 40 kilograms of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will seek to eliminate its reserve by 2012, according to the joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly due to Lukashenko's harsh crackdown on human rights.
But Wednesday's statement suggested a potential detente.
It stated that 'while welcoming progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains a central issue for improving bilateral relations, and is essential to the progress of the country and its citizens.'
