Secondly, the recovery of the framework, although it now seems science fiction, with a very favorable opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third is a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines for offending countries, possible suspension of payments by some of them and the extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a divergence between what Germany believed should be done (tax austerity plans and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second on the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully prolonged the decision to bail out Greece.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were strongly against the bailout of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union's treaties, to make it possible to rescue a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, because it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat watered down, has been adopted and in the coming months we should be witnessing the process of reform of the Union which will make those measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it will not cross.
And he is telling us all that, even if we now have to take steps with which he may not agree, from that date the old way of working the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which offending countries will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare themselves in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out that we must pursue a tough growth path with high rates of saving and investment, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, is simply not going to be tolerated.
The invitation is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand that.
It is not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they're asking of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is to fool ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will give way to greater calm.
And let's take advantage of the window of opportunity that we've been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after the meeting last Saturday with the big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite the criticisms of Merkel, the thesis that we must put order at home has been opened up.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn't look like it's going to be moved.
And the possibility of leaving a monetary area too full of unserious countries cannot be excluded.
Then Germany can always tell us that it had already warned us.
Sports and Law Fraud
Tricks like Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape a penalty.
The allegedly horrendous expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 Champions League match against Ajax has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behaviour is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with a few minutes to go to the end of the match (which their team had clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when they took out both fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and can go clean of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos, the unwritten, but followed, rules of this sport.
Part of the debate arising in the case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presumes nobility and honor, and that in past occasions has fined its players for analogous acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long technical history of histrionic and provocative.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the rules is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions are fraudulent; indeed, they are actions respectful of the sporting rules, but they seem to evade their meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of damage they do to sportsmanship.
One of the goods that comprises the sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the players opposite, aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these goods to which fair play refers is to prevent the team of offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not accommodate themselves to what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious so as to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is what kind of advantage the offenders get in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the opponent is not placed in a disadvantageous situation or that a profit is obtained in the same match, since the result of the action evidently implies leaving the team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this performance the players meet a match of sanction and go to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, going round and round, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, such actions do not go against the spirit of the game, which is part of making strategic decisions that favor getting the most out of what the rules allow.
In the present case, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of fraud of the law), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and law-breaking is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I believe, arises from two factors: because there were two self-evictions and because of the way in which the directive to bring about them was transmitted.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
