Pakistan's nuclear program is causing great concern in the US
Islamabad produces atomic weapons at "a rate faster than any other country".
The Wikileaks leaks confirm the links between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The contents of the correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirm the enormous concerns that the Pakistani nuclear program causes in Washington.
Aside from the enlightening and juicy details of the content of the talks and the thoughts of the US diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries on atomic security, instead of increasing, is "decreasing", and that the unstable Asian country is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The particularity of Pakistan's nuclear programme - that the weapons are not assembled but stored in components to make it harder to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for the Washington alarm.
Ambassador to Pakistan Anne W. Patterson, in a report prior to the visit of then National Security Adviser James Jones, lists: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under attack by the Taliban, the rumored dispersion of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials".
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programmes is considered, not only by the US but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to be on guard.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the fall in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people to work on nuclear or missile programs", Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said at a meeting with his US counterparts.
The most novel of the documents leaked by Julian Assange's portal is the decreasing cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and the high pace of Pakistani nuclear weapons production.
An embassy dispatch in May, calling communication with Pakistan "frustrating", said: "Transparency is often lacking; offers of help are unanswered or dismissed".
In another tweet, Peter Lavoy, National Intelligence officer for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
Ambassador Patterson also asked Washington, during a visit by Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani, to make "very clear" to the official that "the Pakistan Army must end its tacit support for terrorist groups".
The hunt for the head of Wikileaks
Obama appoints a senior counterterrorism official to prevent further leaks.
Interpol is issuing a red alert in order to track the movements and locate Assange wherever he is.
Everything about WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated maze where it's hard to be certain about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a "red alert" to "locate and track the movements" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
Besides, it's not new, it's dated November 20th.
And it's not about the latest leak of over a quarter of a million US diplomatic documents, but about the sexual abuse allegations the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer of the creator of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, assures that "the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange".
It was on the 20th when the international police body based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
As it is, all 188 Interpol countries have indication of identifying or locating Assange "with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many member countries, as the organization has explained, do consider the so-called red notice a free way to proceed with an arrest - which must be undertaken by the national police body, especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move has angered Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing that the 39-year-old Wikileaks founder has shown willingness to answer questions from Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor in his case, whom they compare to the mythical Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's head of security.
"This looks like a hunt, not a legal persecution", the letter says.
While the world is searching for him - and from Australia his mother defends her son's innocence - Assange remains unaccounted for, but not silent.
On Monday he gave an undisclosed interview to the editor of Time magazine via Skype, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering American diplomats to spy on the UN in violation of international treaties that the US has signed, he should resign", he said.
His opinion was denounced yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not entirely sure why we should care about the opinion of a guy with a website", he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a top counterterrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks of documents.
President Barack Obama's spokesman's attempt to downplay Assange contrasts with the views being voiced by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the House Homeland Security Committee in January, has asked the State Department to consider putting WikiLeaks on the terrorist list "to intervene and fund it and prosecute anyone who gives it any input or help".
Furthermore, Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, has had to backtrack after saying that Assange should "be killed".
"Obama should make it a target and use a drone or something".
The one who didn't apologize was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and a possible candidate for president.
"Whoever in the government leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything but execution would be a too-kind punishment", he declared on Fox.
