Huguet proposes a more plural executive and the end of the assembly system.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found the recipe to avoid the umpteenth internal revolt in the ERC ranks, with the loss of 11 deputies and half the votes.
The party president is aware that his amago of resignation is insufficient for those who are related to former leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira, but he also knows that the influence of that sector is today as diluted as his own mentor and that it can absolutely cause him the headaches he had with other extinct currents.
The leader of Esquerra will try to win over the new critics with winking that will allow him to arm until the municipal elections.
To begin with, Puigcercós announced yesterday that the more than 200 national councillors of the ERC will be able to decide on its continuation in secret.
By ballot, not by show of hands.
If the carodians want to deliver a certain vow of punishment to the president, they can do so without fear of retaliation.
In fact, the rank-and-file leader wants to avoid the image of division as much as that of submission to his person.
In several interviews, he said that it would not be considered ratified with half plus one of the votes, but added, without specifying percentages, that it would also not be good a result "to the Bulgarian".
Those close to Carod demand that the president do more than make his position available to the militancia, a gesture that is not valid when Puigcercós controls the highest organ between congresses.
But since they don't have a majority to force resignations, they're going to try to agree with the executive a road map between now and May.
To do so, they hope to participate in the drafting of the strategic reorientation document that the management will submit to the national council for a vote on the 18th.
Their intention is to endorse Puigcercós in exchange for his promise to move the congress forward to the autumn of 2011, something that the top leadership already takes for granted.
The ERC leader acknowledged that "polyphony" is detrimental to stability and that his goal is to make the organization, once and for all, able to wash the dirty rags from doors in.
In this line, the article that the acting minister Josep Huguet signed on his blog is symptomatic.
Considering Puigcercós' ideologist, the head of Innovació took it for granted that the leader would be endorsed "in exchange for various objectives".
And he listed five, of which two stand out.
The first is to "re-compose" the executive so that it represents at least 90% of the membership, that is, to include new faces from the sector related to Carod.
The second one might be the big news.
Huguet proposes that ERC should abolish assemblyism as a mechanism of operation.
It therefore advocates a reform of the statutes to allow congresses to be held by delegates elected by suffrage.
The end of the assembly model, an exception in the Spanish party system, has been an obsession of the Puigcercós team, which has already fought in this direction in the last two congresses.
In fact, the convulsive conclave of 2008 left the task of revising the assembly in a specific congress of statutes reform to the leadership.
This appointment is still pending, as the internal tide of recent years has made it advisable not to tackle the matter.
Now, with no critical sectors lurking, it might be a good time to take it back and try to shut it down for good.
