China maintains targets to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of that country at COP16 assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that it maintains its offer to reduce by 2020 between 40 and 45 percent of its greenhouse gas emissions.
China is sticking to its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, China's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said that his country has made tremendous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, in the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China would not change its objectives but would continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
He said China's climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and support for pilot programmes.
In all these areas there have been progress, including the approval, last year, of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set in terms of reducing gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the federal authorities have been working in a coordinated manner with the state and local authorities to achieve the objectives of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, there are a number of multiannual plans, funded by the Chinese government and other governments, which are either underway or have already been completed.
For example, he mentioned the Energy Efficiency Program, which has been implemented for the past five years and which received investments from the United Nations Organization (UN), the government and the private sector.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent bulbs for savers and another for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, scientific adviser to the government of that country on climate change, assured that China's efforts have been greater than what is generally thought.
For example, he pointed out, China's per capita emissions of greenhouse gases are six tons per person, while the United States' is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the last five years and plans to do the same by 2020, he said.
