Obama promotes on Twitter law in favor of undocumented students
"If you agree that passing the Dream Act is the right thing to do, call your senators and get them to pass this legislation", the US president tweeted on the popular social network.
President Barack Obama joined the nationwide mobilization in support of the Dream Act, to legalize undocumented students, with a message on his personal Twitter account.
"If you agree that passing the Dream Act is the right thing to do, call your senators and urge them to pass this legislation", Obama tweeted.
His brief message maintains an open cyberlink to a broader document that asks the public to immediately contact senators, given that the vote on the legislation is imminent.
"With a vote expected soon, now is the time to make your voice heard", he notes.
The message was released after 42 Republican senators threatened to block the vote on any legislation unless Bush-era tax cuts and government funding are extended.
Such a blockade, announced in a letter signed by 42 Republican senators, could affect the vote on the Dream Act and other bills such as ratification of the new START treaty with Russia against the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
Questioned by the Republican blockade of the Dream Act and other projects, presidential spokesman Robert Gibbs said that once the tax issue is resolved, a timetable can be set for the rest of the projects.
"I think there's a lot of time...
"We all agree that we have to resolve the fiscal issue before the end of the year... "
"I think we can reach an agreement at some point on that and then we can plan the sequence of the rest", he said.
Senate Democratic Majority Leader Harry Reid announced Tuesday that he would call for a "closure vote" for the Dream Act, so the initiative to legalize undocumented students could be voted on starting next Thursday in the Senate, though it's more likely next week.
The Senate version of the Dream Act would legalize some 800,000 young people who entered the United States before the age of 16, have been in the country for the past five years, and have entered a higher education institution or the military.
But supporters require 60 votes to approve the bill, which requires the help of a handful of Republicans, as pro-project organizations are engaged in intense lobbying to ensure passage of the bill.
The Democrats, most of whom support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
However at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, has said he will vote against, and only one Republican has expressed support for the bill, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
That's why the Dream Act supporters are calling for a number of Republicans to join them in case other Democrats decide to turn their backs on the bill.
Among the most courted Republicans are the Maine Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, as well as outgoing Senator George Lemieux of Florida, who completed the term of Senator Mel Martinez.
Other Republicans who supported the Dream Act in the past include Orrin Hatch of Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas, but have stated that they will not support it in the future.
Another Republican he supported, John McCain, has not defined his stance at this time.
While the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the Dream Act faces the biggest obstacles in the Senate.
