US changes rules for visa
Individuals should go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres before their interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and so will the waiting time.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa application procedure at the US Embassy and consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service (ASC) before their interview at the Consular Section.
The applicant's biometric information will be taken by the ASC staff, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer will it be necessary to make a payment for arranging the appointment, another payment for processing the visa application and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-off payment covering all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa-on-demand cases (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second interview appointment at the Consular Section will be in the Consular Section for a shorter time than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26 USD.
The new visa application procedure is available at http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html for further information on the new visa application procedure.
