A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by an amount that corresponds to almost a third of the additional reduction that must be carried out to stabilize the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major concrete projects that the UN hopes to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolise between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, even better, by light emitting diode (LED) bulbs, much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's equivalent to 70% of the planet's car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this quantity should be reduced to stabilise the temperature rise by two degrees Celsius by 2020 to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95 percent of the energy is dissipated as heat, and the rest, or 5 percent, is produced as light.
In the case of fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by a further twofold.
Fluorescent bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company which also took part in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives us an idea of the savings that could be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also run on rheostats and emit very little heat.
On top of that, they don't contain any mercury.
Various experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless the manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not fluorescent bulbs but coal-fired power plants, which emit large amounts of mercury to produce the electricity that is spilled by incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would bring to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity and 8 million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power stations that would cost 2.5 billion.
