Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case is a two-pronged issue.
On the one hand, it exposes an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press cuttings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculous profile of Gaddafi has long been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of news that is public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a library devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each work (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who engage in occultism do not just rely on what they already know, which confirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to classified files.
The informant is lazy, just as the head of the secret services is lazy (or has little desire) (if he could not be, I don't know, editor of Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same information that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why have the revelations in these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they are simply saying what every educated person knows already, namely that embassies, at least since the Second World War and since Heads of State can telephone one another or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some limited representation exercises, have been transformed into centres of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this well, we just pretend we don't know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could access the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world would significantly affect the State Department's prestige.
The scandal therefore affects both the victims and the "victims".
But let's get into the real nature of what happened.
In the old days, in Orwell's time, you could think of all power as a Big Brother controlling the every move of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has been fulfilled since, by being able to control every move thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it's shown, as it is now, that even the cryptos of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can you stand a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be disclosed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without a secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury to such a powerful power?
It is clear that in future, the States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the net, since it would be like putting it on a sign in the middle of the street.
But it also becomes clear that with today's technology, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has flown in and made contact with one of his counterparts.
How will you be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know that my prediction is science fiction and therefore novel, but I imagine government officials traveling discreetly on stagecoaches with uncontrollable routes, carrying messages they have memorized or, at best, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then stored, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I've written that technology is currently moving like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has created a wired telegraph (telephony) again.
Video tapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, going forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now CDs (digital) only allow one to go forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel involved, we need three and a half hours.
So it is not at all unusual that politics and communication techniques lead us back to the horse-drawn carriages.
One last note.
In the old days, the press tried to understand what was going on in the embassies.
Today, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: French funding promises are in tatters
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the promises of rapidly unblocked financing (called fast start or precoces) made by the developed countries have been respected.
And the French screw-ups have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to providing 7.2 billion euro over three years and France 1.260 billion euro (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU put its best cards on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is real: a report detailing the measures taken by its Member States, a press conference, a major side event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparency operation was appreciated and appreciated for what it's really worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
The Copenhagen Accord calls for money to be 'new and additional' to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonization, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, each person chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added over three years as a fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks for the year or level of official development assistance.
The Commission notes that the French authorities have not provided any evidence that the aid was granted in the form of a loan.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of French aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to 'new and additional' funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and each one chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, consider each euro borrowed to be a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments which are profitable (often emission reduction projects based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro which is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro which is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be computed for its commitments.
But France does not find this reasoning useful: it "meets" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of grants (36.1 million euros); see the EU document for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union which uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses 46% of the funds, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, meet their commitments with 100% of the donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is committing a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the actual financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional" as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has been handling the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not fools...
The early financing chapter is a relatively short-term detail in the overall climate negotiations.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is imperative to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But France could in particular help to advance the debate on the stakes involved in longterm financing (another essential chapter under discussion at the moment): we will not get rid of the question of the 'additional character' or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive in relation to this issue as it is with others.
So we have the hope of the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will be arriving in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of the 'additional character' and use of the loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
