The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that are likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although in virtually all cases the legal limits for each chemical are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE pollutants is of concern", the association said.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogens and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil and intended as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in the food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the Russian steak, the canned tuna, and even the bread or gum were laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
The test results showed nitrates and chloroform in the tap water.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritious" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk to the consumer from these "cocktails of pollutants" "is likely to be underestimated", says the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in view of the seriousness of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) found residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of which were in cereals.
